<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911011-0002</DOCNO><DOCID>911011-0002.</DOCID><HL>   Former J.P. Morgan   Official Agrees to Ban,   Fine in Insider Case</HL><DATE>10/11/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C9</SO><CO>   JPM LPLI</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>MAJOR MONEY CENTER BANKS (BAN)ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)SECURITIES REGULATIONS AND ENFORCEMENT (RGU)SECURITIES (SCR)</IN><NS>SECURITIES REGULATION (RGU)</NS><GV>SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A former J.P. Morgan executive hasagreed to a five-year ban from the securities industry andwill pay more than $270,000 in penalties to settle insidertrading charges, officials said yesterday.   The Securities and Exchange Commission accused RushtonLeigh Ardrey Jr. of making $129,586 in illegal profit fromtrading in the stock of LPL Technologies Inc. while hepossessed confidential information about a pending leveragedbuy-out.</LP><TEXT>   LPL, based in Wallingford, Conn., makes connectors andcoaxial cable. A J.P. Morgan andamp; Co. subsidiary owned a 20%stake in LPL.   Without admitting or denying wrongdoing, Mr. Ardrey, ofNew York, agreed to a minimum five-year ban from any dealingswith the industry. He also agreed to pay a total of $270,063in alleged illegal profit, fines and interest.   The civil complaint filed in federal court in New Yorksaid Mr. Ardrey, a former senior vice president with Morgan,began buying LPL stock on Jan. 5, 1990, one day afterlearning from another Morgan executive that LPL's managementplanned a leveraged buy-out and would offer $24 a share tostockholders.   The SEC alleged that Ardrey purchased 18,000 LPL sharesfor an average of $16.83 a share over three months and soldthem for an average of $24.38 each after the tender offer wasannounced March 19, 1990.   Federal securities law forbids corporate officers,investment bankers, merger lawyers and other insiders fromtrading on information that hasn't been made public, tomaintain the investing public's confidence that the stockmarkets are not rigged in favor of insiders.</TEXT></DOC>